snippet.textDisplay:
none of those are, or ever were, 'blade' putters. nobody has even made an actual blade putter in at least 70 years. a blade putter looks like a 1-iron with less loft.
if you ever see one, it will almost definitely be on a hickory shaft. i have one i use as a cane. an old spalding. and i actually putt pretty well with it on lightning fast greens.
none of those putters are even 'modern blades.' the most famous example of a 'modern blade' is an acushnet bullseye. thats what a blade looks like.
nobody makes a blade putter anymore. just stop saying blade unless your talking about forged steel irons. you can say it then if you want to. lol :)

snippet.textDisplay: The swinging-gate style heel-shafted blade-putter is very overrated for the amateur, fat-hands/ fat-fingers (not necessarily long thin hands) type guy. It takes  thinner hands and fingers with the touch of a good painter to hone it in consistently. (I can’t even read my own name written in my cursive handwriting). Tons of practice, very small precise motion of back and thru to get the exact closing motion to strike the ball on the right spot. Needs to be rethought for the amateur. This putter, on the other hand, is great for the 80’s-90’s weekend golfer. Fit that with thing with a flatso super stroke (hands together putting motion) and it is a guaranteed bucket without 10 hours a week on the putting green. Pick one up. Even if you don’t like it they’ll still be bringing in close to retail on eBay for a long time. I’m telling youse dudes. I can’t wait to get one! Center-shafted mallet all the way with the super stroke fatso grip. Can’t wait, son, can’t wait!

snippet.textDisplay: So the marketing has got you, Rick. The actual triangle truss itself has utterly zero effect whatsoever compared to a one without. The only thing different with those putters is the head location, and thats what they're selling with the putters. If you draw an imaginary line from the grip to the putter face, it doesn't matter if theres a truss, if theres a stick thin offset, or if the shaft itself starts adding loop-de-loops and S shapes, its all the same. Its only about where that imaginary line would meet, and for these putters that would be closer towards centre.
snippet.textOriginal: So the marketing has got you, Rick. The actual triangle truss itself has utterly zero effect whatsoever compared to a one without. The only thing different with those putters is the head location, and thats what they're selling with the putters. If you draw an imaginary line from the grip to the putter face, it doesn't matter if theres a truss, if theres a stick thin offset, or if the shaft itself starts adding loop-de-loops and S shapes, its all the same. Its only about where that imaginary line would meet, and for these putters that would be closer towards centre.
